## system_clock vs steady_clock

C++20 provides two primary clocks for different purposes:

| Clock | Monotonic | When to use |
|-------|-----------|-------------|
| `system_clock` | No (can jump during NTP) | Timestamps, logs, calendar dates |
| `steady_clock` | Yes (always forward) | Measuring elapsed time |

Always use `steady_clock` for benchmarks:

```cpp
auto t0 = std::chrono::steady_clock::now();
// ... code to measure ...
auto t1 = std::chrono::steady_clock::now();
auto elapsed = std::chrono::duration_cast<std::chrono::microseconds>(t1 - t0);
```

For obtaining the current calendar date, use `system_clock`:

```cpp
auto now = std::chrono::system_clock::now();
std::chrono::year_month_day today{std::chrono::floor<std::chrono::days>(now)};
```

## duration_cast, floor, ceil, round

Converting a `duration` to a different unit:

```cpp
std::chrono::milliseconds ms{1750};

duration_cast<seconds>(ms)  // 1 s (truncates toward zero)
floor<seconds>(ms)          // 1 s (toward negative infinity)
ceil<seconds>(ms)           // 2 s (toward positive infinity)
round<seconds>(ms)          // 2 s (to nearest; ties go to even)
```

For non-negative values, `duration_cast` and `floor` produce the same result. The difference appears with negative values.

## Parsing Dates: std::chrono::parse

C++20 adds `std::chrono::parse` â€” the inverse of `std::format`. It's used via `operator>>` with a proxy object:

```cpp
#include <sstream>

std::istringstream ss{"2026-12-31"};
std::chrono::year_month_day ymd;
ss >> std::chrono::parse("%Y-%m-%d", ymd);
// ymd == 2026y/December/31d
```

Same specifiers as `std::format`: `%Y` = year, `%m` = month as number, `%d` = day, `%H:%M:%S` = time. You can parse directly into `sys_seconds`, `sys_days`, `year_month_day`, and other chrono types.

If the string doesn't match the format, the stream enters an error state (`failbit`).

## Practical Date Calculations

Difference between two dates in days:

```cpp
using namespace std::chrono;
int days_between(year_month_day from, year_month_day to) {
    return (sys_days{to} - sys_days{from}).count();
}
```

Day of the week for an arbitrary date:

```cpp
year_month_day date{2026y/December/25d};
weekday wd{sys_days{date}};
std::format("{}", wd);  // "Fri"
```

Notice the pattern: `year_month_day` â†’ `sys_days` is almost always the intermediate step for any computation, because `sys_days` is simply a `time_point<system_clock, days>` on which all `duration` arithmetic operates.

